        "text": "A new film telling men and women's poignant mental health stories is being used to give hope to others.\n\nOf My Kin portrays the heart-rending tales of people who have come together to heal and know first-hand what it is to suffer from mental health issues.\n\nFunded by Armagh City, Banbridge and Craigavon Borough Council and NI Screen and produced in association with Action Mental Health, the film was two years in the making.\n\nThe film, directed and produced by award-winning Northern Ireland film and TV director Joe McStravick, was unveiled at a special launch screening on Tuesday, January 23, at the IMC Banbridge cinema.\n\nThe people who feature in the short film tell of attempted suicide bids, being sectioned in mental institutions, of worthlessness and breakdowns following unemployment, alcoholism, marital separation - but it is a film enshrined in hope, not hopelessness.\n\nThe stories told in the film – voiced over by actors – give insights into the lives of men and women who have found support, companionship, empathy and literally a lifeline, at Action Mental Health New Horizons service.\n\nAction Mental Health New Horizons centres, found in nine locations across Northern Ireland, provide a range of educational and activity-based classes, which give people with mental health issues structure through training and support services, aimed at helping them regain some semblance of their former selves.\n\nJoe McStravick, winner of the Greer Garson Film Award for the 2011 film Chiasma, revealed the film was born from an offshoot of a separate project commissioned by ABC Council.\n\n\"I was filming another subject, on people’s transition into retirement - involving some of the same people - when I realised there was something else, a story on mental health issues that just had to be told,\" he said.\n\n\"I was researching the film, taping people discussing their issues, together, asking a few questions but mostly recording their chats among themselves and soon they got used to me and started to really open up to me about the mental health issues.\n\n\"Soon I had over five hours of audio with amazing stories so it was very difficult encapsulating the diverse issues they faced but I’ve tried to honour their stories and convey their experiences and struggles with the greatest of integrity.\"\n\nAction Mental Health chief executive David Babington added: \"Of My Kin offers a poignant insight into the difficulties people with mental health issues face coping with the routine of daily life and when they find themselves in times of crisis.\n\n\"Moreover, the film offers people undergoing these personal challenges hope; that there is help out there; that there are people out there who understand fully what they’re going through and who can empathise and provide practical and emotional support as well as a raft of courses and specially tailored classes to help give them structure and meaning in their lives.\""
